<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-713-713  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 713 713.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Dec 17 1990 n621 p27(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC plans RF reserve. (Federal Communications Commission; radiofrequency)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robinson, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Federal Communications Commission (FCC) Chmn Al Sikes says thecommission will create a new radio frequency (RF) spectrum reserveto be used for emerging technologies.andP;  A similar move in the 1970sthat created a reserve in the 900-MHz range allowed the FCC toauthorize cellular and specialized mobile radio, air-groundservices and new public safety services, generating economicactivity, jobs and investment opportunities in the private sector.andO;The announcement comes as a result of growing concern that thecurrent spectrum may not offer enough room for new technologies.andO;Legislation was introduced in Congress that would transfer some200 MHz of the government segment into the public domain.andP;  Some ofthe current incumbent technologies will have to move for thereserve to be established.andP;  The commission also will be dealingwith the issue of whether industry or government should have thefinal say in which technologies work.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government RegulationRadio FrequencyTelecommunicationsCommunications TechnologyUnited States. Federal Communications Commission.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>